<h1>
<u>Colin Wilson's Home Page in Oxford</u></h1>
I work in the <a href="http://www.atm.ox.ac.uk/">Department of Atmospheric,
Oceanic, and Planetary Physics</a> at <a href="http://www.ox.ac.uk/">Oxford
University</a>. For my doctoral degree, I developed a <a 
href="http://www.atm.ox.ac.uk/user/wilson/B2WS/">wind sensor</a> for the 
<a href="http://www.beagle2.com/">Beagle 2</a> Mars lander, which was lost on 
arrival in December 2003. 

<p> I now work on the European Space Agency's <a
href="http://www.atm.ox.ac.uk/project/virtis/">Venus Express</a>
mission, mainly on observations of atmospheric dynamics using the <a
href="http://www.rm.iasf.cnr.it/ias-home/Venus-Express/Venus-Express.htm">VIRTIS
instrument</a>. Venus Express was <a 
href="http://www.esa.int/esaSC/SEM56Q638FE_index_0.html"> launched 
successfully on 9 Nov 2005</a>, and is due to arrive at Venus on the 11 
April 2006.


<p> I am also on the Steering Committee for the <a 
href="http://www.aero.jussieu.fr/VEP/">Venus Entry Probe 
mission</a>, which is being proposed to ESA under the Cosmic Vision AO. 
<a href="http://www.atm.ox.ac.uk/user/wilson/VEPoxford/">Click here</a> 
for presentations from, and a report of, the VEP meeting hosted in 
Oxford 24-25 January 2007.

